00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:24.130
or whatever.

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:26.590
But I'm delighted to
be here with you today.

00:01:26.590 --> 00:01:29.080
So the work that I'm
going to be discussing

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:32.800
is work that I
haven't done recently.

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:35.620
It's about workforce planning.

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:37.330
And it was done with the MBTA.

00:01:37.330 --> 00:01:40.990
Principally the results
I'll give are for the MBTA

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:43.660
as it existed 20-odd years ago.

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:47.710
But the issues are exactly
the same then as they are now.

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:58.880
In fact, I gave a summary of
this presentation to Brian

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:03.506
Shortsleeve and some of the
other people at the MBTA

00:02:03.506 --> 00:02:05.850
a year and a half ago, or so.

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:07.289
And they were
thinking about maybe

00:02:07.289 --> 00:02:09.289
they really should
[AUDIO OUT] --thing something

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:10.560
like this again.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:14.150
So what I want to discuss
the problem in general

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:18.518
of the approach that
we've taken to this,

00:02:18.518 --> 00:02:20.810
and then look at three
different levels of the problem.

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:22.640
One is the strategic
level, which

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:25.340
is the long-term
view, which fits

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:28.040
in with Gabriel's
statement about the theme

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:30.620
of this part of the
course being on strategy.

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:34.910
Then the tactical level,
which is shorter range.

00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:38.040
And then the operational level,
which is really short range.

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:41.062
And these are all tightly
connected and interrelated,

00:02:41.062 --> 00:02:42.770
as I hope I'll be able
to explain to you.

00:02:46.310 --> 00:02:49.860
OK, so the challenge
that we have

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:53.780
in this part of the
operations planning

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:56.660
process, if you think
of it that way, is we

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:58.100
want to provide good service.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.010
We've got hopefully a
decent operating plan

00:03:01.010 --> 00:03:02.900
that we've developed
and want to make sure

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.910
that the service that's
delivered is reliable.

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:10.010
That requires decent equipment,
decent infrastructure, and also

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:12.230
a workforce that's
motivated and there

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:17.060
when you need them, which
is pretty much every day.

00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:19.640
So the operations
plan you've all

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:22.160
been through this at
this stage in the course.

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:24.160
So you know what goes
into the operations plans.

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:25.920
So what comes out of
the operations plan

00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:29.510
are a set of schedules,
timetables, runs, or duties

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:32.610
for operators to perform.

00:03:32.610 --> 00:03:37.200
And that require a certain
amount of workforce or--

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:40.230
excuse me for using the term
"manpower," but it's sort

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:44.140
of the workforce that we need.

00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:46.590
So if you don't have the
right level of workforce

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:49.560
available on a particular
day or at a particular time

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:53.820
on that day, then you've
got a problem potentially.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:58.960
If you can buy work
on an overtime basis,

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:01.870
you can do that and at
least not drop any trips.

00:04:01.870 --> 00:04:04.187
That's going to cost
you money though.

00:04:04.187 --> 00:04:06.270
And you may not be able
to get the overtime, which

00:04:06.270 --> 00:04:10.800
will, again, produce unreliable
service through dropped trips.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:15.690
It may also, if some
workers in the workforce

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:19.200
feel that they can rely on
overtime, which gives them

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:23.520
a 50% premium rate, then maybe
you can take more absence time.

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:25.530
So there's a substitution
relationship here

00:04:25.530 --> 00:04:27.690
between absence and overtime.

00:04:27.690 --> 00:04:30.390
So if you rely more
heavily on overtime,

00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:32.010
perhaps your absence
rate will go up.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:33.910
That's not an outcome you want.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:36.480
So you've got to be
very careful about that.

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:38.640
Certainly, if you
can't buy the overtime

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:42.120
and you don't have enough
people on the property

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:44.440
that particular day,
that particular time,

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:47.010
then you can drop trips
because you don't have anyone

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:48.870
to run the bus or
to run the train.

00:04:48.870 --> 00:04:50.460
And that's a
problem because that

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:54.090
produces worse service
reliability, worse customer

00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:54.810
satisfaction.

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:59.170
Politically, it's a very
negative [AUDIO OUT] as well.

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:00.870
And so workforce
planning is actually

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:04.260
a fairly critical piece of
getting from the operations

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:08.085
plan to good service on
the street or on the rails.

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:16.390
This is sort of a high
level view of what

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:19.300
the problem is, as I see it.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:22.600
So on the left of
this chart, you

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:24.850
have the operator availability.

00:05:24.850 --> 00:05:28.720
So that means the number
of drivers you have

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:30.880
available on a particular day.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:34.600
That's affected by the
number of operators

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:37.750
you had available
the previous day.

00:05:37.750 --> 00:05:40.360
If you hired people,
how many people

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:44.420
are coming on to
increase the supply?

00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:47.200
What sort of attrition--
what sort of outflow

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.870
do you have in your workforce
from your previous time, day,

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:51.620
or time period?

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:52.420
What's the absence?

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:53.830
Because those guys
aren't going to be there.

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:56.410
Those people aren't going to
be there to deliver service.

00:05:56.410 --> 00:05:58.470
And of course,
you have a roster,

00:05:58.470 --> 00:06:02.650
so everyone typically works five
days and takes two days off.

00:06:02.650 --> 00:06:04.910
And that rotates
among the workforce.

00:06:04.910 --> 00:06:10.130
So this is the supply side,
in terms of the operator.

00:06:10.130 --> 00:06:13.280
On the demand side, you
have the scheduled service,

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:16.020
which is a result of
your operating plan--

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:18.530
what you want to provide.

00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:22.820
You have unscheduled
service additions.

00:06:22.820 --> 00:06:25.820
And you potentially have
unscheduled service deletions.

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:29.570
For instance, if there's
a school vacation,

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:31.910
you will drop some
school trips--

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:34.610
trips which are primarily
there on high frequency

00:06:34.610 --> 00:06:36.830
routes to provide
school service.

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:39.910
And these don't fit naturally
into the timetable process

00:06:39.910 --> 00:06:42.410
because there's lot of overhead
in developing and timetable,

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:45.600
as I'm sure Gabriel
has explained to you.

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:49.190
So you'll just take those
trips off the table that day.

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:52.190
And those operators are
then available to provide

00:06:52.190 --> 00:06:55.460
other service that you need and
to fill in for absent operators

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:57.980
those days.

00:06:57.980 --> 00:06:59.810
So you've got the supply.

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:01.100
You've got the demand.

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:03.950
And so you're down here
looking at the availability

00:07:03.950 --> 00:07:06.445
versus the supply of drivers.

00:07:06.445 --> 00:07:08.080
I'll call them "drivers."

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:13.040
The technical jargon in the
industry is "operators."

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:16.160
In a perfect world, you'd
have an exact balance

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:18.410
between availability
and demand, and you

00:07:18.410 --> 00:07:21.020
have no additional cost,
and you've got someone

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:22.190
to cover every trip.

00:07:22.190 --> 00:07:24.090
That will never happen.

00:07:24.090 --> 00:07:24.890
Why?

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:28.820
Because the operator
availability is stochastic.

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:30.050
It's uncertain.

00:07:30.050 --> 00:07:32.840
You don't know what the absence
rate is going to be tomorrow.

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:34.520
With the best will in the
world, with the best models

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:36.187
in the world, you
don't know whether I'm

00:07:36.187 --> 00:07:38.660
going to be feeling well
enough to work tomorrow.

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:40.310
So that's a problem.

00:07:40.310 --> 00:07:45.063
And for instance,
in the MBTA, you

00:07:45.063 --> 00:07:47.480
don't know if you going to
have a failure on the Red Line.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.820
You're going to have to
bus parts of the Red Line

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:53.760
tomorrow at 8 o'clock
in the morning, OK.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:58.470
So all of those uncertainties
affect this balance

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:00.960
between the
availability and demand.

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:02.430
So you'll never be here.

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:05.100
I mean, statistically,
it's virtually

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.050
certain you'll never be there.

00:08:07.050 --> 00:08:10.020
You're either going to be over
here, where the availability is

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:11.370
less than the demand.

00:08:11.370 --> 00:08:13.500
In that case, you have
additional time costs,

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:16.260
because you're going to have
to try and buy operators

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:17.400
to work that overtime.

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:23.580
And perhaps more seriously, you
have the risk of dropping trips

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:26.220
if you can't persuade
operators that they should

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:27.480
work the overtime that day.

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:32.625
Or you're over here,
where the availability

00:08:32.625 --> 00:08:33.750
is greater than the demand.

00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:36.150
In that case, you have
additional personnel costs

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:39.900
who aren't going to be used as
productively as you might like.

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:41.970
If they were going to
be used productively,

00:08:41.970 --> 00:08:44.520
you'd have built them
into the operating plan.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:48.600
So they're probably not going
to be used as productively

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:50.190
as your average operator.

00:08:50.190 --> 00:08:52.880
So this is sort of one way
of looking at the framework.

00:08:56.260 --> 00:09:02.020
We can think of, again, three
levels of planning here.

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:06.040
At the strategic level,
this is typically

00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:09.250
looking at a one-year or even
longer than one year horizon.

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:11.920
So it's not strategic in
terms of infrastructure.

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:15.120
It's strategic in
terms of operations.

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.720
So that's how many
people will we

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:23.270
need in the driver workforce
over the next 12 months.

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:29.050
And how do we get
a hiring plan that

00:09:29.050 --> 00:09:33.700
will give us the right number
of people throughout the year?

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:36.150
How do we allocate
our vacations?

00:09:36.150 --> 00:09:39.460
Do we have a certain
vacation liability?

00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:44.140
If I'm a 20-year employee of
the MBTA in the commons union,

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:48.380
I probably have about five weeks
vacation time over the year.

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:51.730
So I get my five weeks.

00:09:51.730 --> 00:09:53.590
But the MBTA
management decisions

00:09:53.590 --> 00:09:57.020
include when to provide
the vacation allocation.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:09:59.800
So you may have an overall
life vacation liability

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:04.560
of 2,000 vacation weeks.

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:06.750
So the question of
the strategic level,

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:11.820
how do you allocate those 2,000
weeks of vacation liability

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.687
over the course of the year?

00:10:13.687 --> 00:10:15.270
And there are good
ways of doing that.

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:17.950
And there are bad
ways of doing that.

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:20.340
I mean, if you give
vacation liability

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:22.440
when people don't want
to take vacations,

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:24.740
what's likely to happen?

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:26.682
Your absence rate's
going to increase.

00:10:26.682 --> 00:10:28.390
So you really want to
give vacations when

00:10:28.390 --> 00:10:30.280
people want to take vacations.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:32.743
But you don't want to
give them so much vacation

00:10:32.743 --> 00:10:34.660
when they want to take
vacation that it really

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:36.250
costs you a lot more money.

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:38.650
In that case, maybe
taking a higher absence

00:10:38.650 --> 00:10:40.610
will be a better way
of dealing with that.

00:10:40.610 --> 00:10:42.250
So there are really
important questions

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:46.900
on how to meet the
vacation liability.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:48.460
And this is the timetable.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:50.760
We've decided what
we need in terms

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:53.290
of finding decent service.

00:10:53.290 --> 00:10:54.670
And then, at the
strategic level,

00:10:54.670 --> 00:10:58.480
I'd also include
personnel policies.

00:10:58.480 --> 00:11:01.850
So as I think you all
know, in many agencies,

00:11:01.850 --> 00:11:04.090
including the MBTA,
you have a mix

00:11:04.090 --> 00:11:06.140
of part-timers and full-timers.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:08.323
In the MBTA, you have
Management Rights Act, which

00:11:08.323 --> 00:11:09.490
I'm sure you've heard about.

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:12.330
Maybe Fred'll talk
about that next week.

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:14.920
It's a very interesting topic.

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:20.500
And Fred will make a meal
of it, I guarantee that.

00:11:20.500 --> 00:11:26.680
So the MBTA management was given
these rights by the legislature

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:29.350
35 years ago, 36 years ago.

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:35.610
And so they cannot negotiate
about not using part-timers.

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:37.770
That's not part of the
contract negotiation.

00:11:37.770 --> 00:11:40.810
That's a right they've
been given legally.

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:42.570
It's been challenged
in the courts.

00:11:42.570 --> 00:11:43.680
It's been upheld.

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:45.870
And so they will
use part-timers.

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:48.390
They've decided to use
part-timers in a way

00:11:48.390 --> 00:11:50.970
that I think is
very unproductive.

00:11:50.970 --> 00:11:56.710
They use part-timers as
apprentice full-timers.

00:11:56.710 --> 00:11:59.710
And so someone suffers
through perhaps five years

00:11:59.710 --> 00:12:02.440
as a part-timer at
the MBTA in order

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:06.740
to reach nirvana of being
a full-timer at the MBTA.

00:12:06.740 --> 00:12:10.310
Well, that's one
way of doing it.

00:12:10.310 --> 00:12:13.630
But I'm not sure that's
the best way of doing it.

00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:15.970
Perhaps what you're
doing is, you're

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:19.720
making these part-timers
suffer for five years,

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:22.210
if that's how long it takes
to get promoted from part-time

00:12:22.210 --> 00:12:23.085
to full-timer status.

00:12:23.085 --> 00:12:25.090
So they're sort of unhappy
for that five years,

00:12:25.090 --> 00:12:28.590
because that's not
what they want.

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:31.210
And it's pretty miserable
working conditions.

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:32.850
They don't get full benefits.

00:12:32.850 --> 00:12:39.480
And typically, they work a
6-hour day spread over 13

00:12:39.480 --> 00:12:40.260
hours--

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:42.480
so covering the AM
peak and the PM peak.

00:12:42.480 --> 00:12:45.610
And they're doing nothing
between the AM peak and PM

00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:46.110
peak.

00:12:46.110 --> 00:12:47.670
You hope they're not in bars.

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:49.337
But they're certainly
not doing anything

00:12:49.337 --> 00:12:52.230
productive with the property.

00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:54.620
So that's the way
the MBTA decides

00:12:54.620 --> 00:12:56.520
to use the management
rights they

00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:58.320
were given by the legislature.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:00.160
I don't think that
was a good decision.

00:13:00.160 --> 00:13:03.810
If you have separate
AM part-timers,

00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:06.840
might you be able to
increase your workforce?

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:08.100
I think so.

00:13:08.100 --> 00:13:11.640
You have people-- shop clerks
who don't really start work

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:14.190
until after the
AM peak who might

00:13:14.190 --> 00:13:19.290
be very interested in
supplementing their shop clerk

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:23.220
job by having an
AM-peak driving job.

00:13:23.220 --> 00:13:26.280
And similarly, in the
PM peak, you probably

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:28.920
can increase your
labor pool with people

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:32.940
who are not interested in a
full-time MBTA driver's job,

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:36.930
but they would be interested
in just a sort of a guaranteed,

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:39.670
3-hour piece of work every day.

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:42.150
So there are lots of different
ways of implementing this.

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:46.280
And I'm pretty sure the
MBTA didn't do it optimally.

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:49.860
So that's what I mean
by personnel policies.

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:52.760
So all of these are at
the strategic level.

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:57.020
At the tactical level, what
we're making decisions on

00:13:57.020 --> 00:14:02.270
is the time horizon is
typically one timetable.

00:14:02.270 --> 00:14:05.653
How many timetables does
the MBTA have per year?

00:14:05.653 --> 00:14:06.278
AUDIENCE: Four.

00:14:06.278 --> 00:14:07.960
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yeah, four.

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:09.940
So you're making
these decisions,

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:12.430
running up to each timetable--

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:14.800
the start of each
timetable period.

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:18.730
And the main decisions
are the staff.

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:22.240
And you've sort of got
your workforce fixed.

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:23.980
And you're deciding
how to allocate them

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:30.110
across depots or garages or rail
lines and by days of the week.

00:14:30.110 --> 00:14:32.920
Those are the tactical-level
decisions you're making.

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:35.690
Those, it turns out, are
actually quite important.

00:14:35.690 --> 00:14:38.235
If you make poor
decisions, then you're

00:14:38.235 --> 00:14:40.360
going to be providing less
reliable service or more

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:44.020
expensive service than
you otherwise would.

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:47.140
And then at the final level,
your operational level,

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:52.450
is here we are 4
o'clock on a Thursday.

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:54.220
At 12 o'clock today--

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:57.280
so four hours ago--
the MBTA was deciding

00:14:57.280 --> 00:15:01.450
when to ask each extra
board operator to show up

00:15:01.450 --> 00:15:05.020
for work tomorrow if they didn't
have a guaranteed assignment.

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:06.310
OK?

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:10.430
So there are unexpected absences
that will occur tomorrow.

00:15:10.430 --> 00:15:12.340
You don't know when
they're going to occur.

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:13.715
You don't know
whether it's going

00:15:13.715 --> 00:15:16.840
to be an AM report or a PM
report or whatever it is.

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:19.510
And you have to make
the decision about when,

00:15:19.510 --> 00:15:21.700
if you have five extra
board operators that

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:23.740
don't have an assignment,
because a known,

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:27.640
in advance absence, when
you want them to show up?

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:31.000
And that the daily report times
for unassigned, extra staff

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.060
is the operational-level
decision.

00:15:35.060 --> 00:15:37.160
Any questions about
this, in terms

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:41.240
of strategic,
operational, tactical?

00:15:41.240 --> 00:15:46.740
And I'm not talking here about
policies that may change--

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:48.630
absenteeism, for instance.

00:15:48.630 --> 00:15:50.910
Fred will talk about
some of those next week

00:15:50.910 --> 00:15:52.620
when he talks about
labor relations.

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:57.510
But I'm talking about sort of a
narrower piece of this puzzle.

00:15:57.510 --> 00:15:58.900
Any questions on this?

00:15:58.900 --> 00:15:59.640
Yes, Kenji?

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:05.083
AUDIENCE: [? Someone ?] become
the part-time operator--

00:16:05.083 --> 00:16:06.000
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yeah.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:09.428
AUDIENCE: So are they
required any license or--

00:16:09.428 --> 00:16:10.470
NIGEL HM WILSON: Oh, yes.

00:16:10.470 --> 00:16:13.920
A commercial driver's
license is required for them.

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:18.360
But again, what I
was saying is, you

00:16:18.360 --> 00:16:25.410
have choice about both who to
recruit into those positions--

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:29.970
do we want an AM part-timer
or a split-shift, full-day

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:31.830
part-timer who's
going to be unhappy

00:16:31.830 --> 00:16:35.610
until they get their
full-time position at the MBTA

00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:36.940
that they really want.

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:37.920
So yeah, sorry.

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:41.110
The other point I wanted
to make is that how

00:16:41.110 --> 00:16:45.040
you select those people who
will get promoted to full-timer.

00:16:45.040 --> 00:16:47.610
So you've decided,
through attrition

00:16:47.610 --> 00:16:50.400
in the full-time ranks, you want
to promote some part-timers.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:52.570
How do you make that promotion?

00:16:52.570 --> 00:16:55.710
Do you promote based
strictly on seniority?

00:16:55.710 --> 00:16:58.740
In other words, the first
one to become a part-timer

00:16:58.740 --> 00:17:02.160
becomes the first one to be
promoted to a full-timer?

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:04.200
Probably not,
because you'd really

00:17:04.200 --> 00:17:08.130
like people who are motivated,
who have a good absence record,

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:09.480
a good accident record.

00:17:09.480 --> 00:17:13.140
So you'd like to use criteria in
that promotion, which are more

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:15.609
than just strict seniority.

00:17:15.609 --> 00:17:18.400
And the MBTA, again,
has been, I would say,

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:22.670
not very effective in using
that balance between seniority,

00:17:22.670 --> 00:17:24.760
which is an important issue--

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:29.080
you want to avoid favoritism and
discrimination in the promotion

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:29.890
process--

00:17:29.890 --> 00:17:33.370
with having some
elements of performance

00:17:33.370 --> 00:17:37.435
in the promotion
process, I would argue.

00:17:37.435 --> 00:17:38.560
Did I answer your question?

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:39.647
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:17:39.647 --> 00:17:40.730
NIGEL HM WILSON: Go ahead.

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:42.355
AUDIENCE: I was
interested in the topic

00:17:42.355 --> 00:17:47.340
because, yeah, we have a similar
culture for the station's

00:17:47.340 --> 00:17:47.960
time--

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:48.470
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:49.345
AUDIENCE: --in Japan.

00:17:49.345 --> 00:17:55.922
But for the driver, they
require a very strict license--

00:17:55.922 --> 00:17:56.880
NIGEL HM WILSON: Right.

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:58.713
AUDIENCE: --which takes
a long time to test.

00:17:58.713 --> 00:18:00.730
So we don't have any
part-time drivers.

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:01.800
NIGEL HM WILSON: Right.

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:02.580
Right, yes.

00:18:02.580 --> 00:18:06.360
And there are commercial
driver's licenses

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:07.380
required for the MBTA.

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:10.890
A bus driver or train driver has
to have a commercial driver's

00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:11.910
license.

00:18:11.910 --> 00:18:16.170
But it's not as a rigorous and
long period of qualification

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:17.860
as it is, I'm sure in JR-East.

00:18:17.860 --> 00:18:20.430
That would be my guess, anyway.

00:18:20.430 --> 00:18:22.080
Any other comments or questions?

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:24.460
OK.

00:18:24.460 --> 00:18:30.430
OK, so let's look at this
as three levels of planning.

00:18:30.430 --> 00:18:33.880
So strategic level-- we're
deciding the workforce size,

00:18:33.880 --> 00:18:36.280
vacation allocation
over the year,

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:40.940
and hiring patterns over
the course of a year.

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:43.840
So by period of the
year, the input into this

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:46.570
includes absence hours.

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:49.570
If we know we typically
have more absence hours

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:52.660
in the winter because the
conditions are miserable--

00:18:52.660 --> 00:18:54.850
you don't drive
in snow and ice--

00:18:54.850 --> 00:18:58.330
and if you have observed
higher absence rates,

00:18:58.330 --> 00:19:00.820
that's important in
making the right decisions

00:19:00.820 --> 00:19:04.220
on the strategic level.

00:19:04.220 --> 00:19:05.390
Required extra work.

00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:11.210
If we know that we are going
to be bussing on the Braintree

00:19:11.210 --> 00:19:13.667
branch of the Red Line
because of reconstruction,

00:19:13.667 --> 00:19:16.000
then we'll build that into
our workforce planning thing.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.230
So that's an example
of required extra work.

00:19:18.230 --> 00:19:20.360
And attrition--
we do projections

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:23.510
about the number of
full-timers and part-timers

00:19:23.510 --> 00:19:29.150
who will be retiring or leaving
the productive workforce

00:19:29.150 --> 00:19:32.360
over the next year.

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:35.510
On the right-hand side, we
have input such as budget,

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:39.260
the service plan, the operations
plan, vacation liability--

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:42.740
how much vacation do we have
to provide in the next year--

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:46.730
work rules and policies
that we want to meet.

00:19:46.730 --> 00:19:49.820
And what I'm showing
here is strategic level,

00:19:49.820 --> 00:19:54.200
tactical level, and
operational level.

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:57.980
And what you'll see is
these downward arrows

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:01.340
from strategy to
tactics to operations,

00:20:01.340 --> 00:20:04.340
and the upward
pointing arrows back

00:20:04.340 --> 00:20:08.570
up the chain from operations
to tactical to strategic.

00:20:08.570 --> 00:20:12.230
So let's explain
each of these arrows.

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:17.850
The downward arrows represent
constraints on your decisions.

00:20:17.850 --> 00:20:21.050
So if you've made some
strategic-level decisions

00:20:21.050 --> 00:20:23.390
on workforce size,
that limits what you

00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:25.220
can do at the tactical level.

00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:27.860
And that's this
downward arrow here.

00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:31.250
Similarly, you make your
tactical-level decisions

00:20:31.250 --> 00:20:33.030
at the beginning of
a timetable, that

00:20:33.030 --> 00:20:35.030
limits what you can do
at the operational level.

00:20:35.030 --> 00:20:38.180
These are these
downward-pointing arrows

00:20:38.180 --> 00:20:40.040
between these boxes.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:44.480
The upward pointing arrows
are the relationships

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:47.540
between that you need
to know about how

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:51.890
efficiently the operations
level is conducted

00:20:51.890 --> 00:20:56.030
to make good decisions at the
higher levels of the planning

00:20:56.030 --> 00:20:58.800
hierarchy.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:05.390
So for instance, if you know
that overtime is virtually

00:21:05.390 --> 00:21:07.130
impossible to get
from your workforce,

00:21:07.130 --> 00:21:09.000
for whatever reason--
they may say,

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.170
I'm just not going to cooperate,
I'm not going to work,

00:21:12.170 --> 00:21:16.760
or that could be bad or
good reasons for that--

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:18.710
then you need to
know that in order

00:21:18.710 --> 00:21:22.430
to make the right decisions
at the tactical level.

00:21:22.430 --> 00:21:24.500
And similarly, you need
to know that to make

00:21:24.500 --> 00:21:27.365
the right decisions at
the strategic level.

00:21:27.365 --> 00:21:30.990
So these are these
upward-pointing arrows here.

00:21:30.990 --> 00:21:35.220
And the difference in the
inputs are just more detail.

00:21:35.220 --> 00:21:39.500
So absence hours by
garage and by day of week

00:21:39.500 --> 00:21:44.850
is important input into
the tactical level.

00:21:44.850 --> 00:21:48.290
Absence hours by
garage and time of day

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:54.420
is important input into
the operational level, OK.

00:21:54.420 --> 00:21:55.930
And you have work
rules and policies

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:58.360
as critical inputs
on all these levels.

00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:07.650
So this is a slightly different
look at these relationships.

00:22:10.170 --> 00:22:15.110
And I want to lead you
through this a little bit.

00:22:15.110 --> 00:22:17.810
So this is our
strategic planning box

00:22:17.810 --> 00:22:20.300
where we're deciding
workforce size.

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:21.140
What goes into this?

00:22:21.140 --> 00:22:23.030
The unit costs--
how much does it

00:22:23.030 --> 00:22:27.050
cost to provide a
platform hour, which

00:22:27.050 --> 00:22:30.650
is an hour of driving
a bus, by an overtime

00:22:30.650 --> 00:22:34.670
employee, a full-time employee,
and a part-time employee?

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:38.300
Those are very important,
basic cost units

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:41.520
that we need to have.

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:43.630
What's the budget, and
what are the work rules?

00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:46.260
The work rules are important
because they tell us

00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:51.713
how easy it will be
to do certain things.

00:22:51.713 --> 00:22:53.630
And I'll give you an
example of that later on.

00:22:53.630 --> 00:22:55.693
And of course, you have
the scheduled hours,

00:22:55.693 --> 00:22:57.110
which comes out
of your operations

00:22:57.110 --> 00:23:01.300
plan-- the timetable
requirements.

00:23:01.300 --> 00:23:04.980
So given that you've made a
decision on the workforce size

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:10.780
at the strategic level,
on a particular day,

00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:14.110
you may have an
amount of open work.

00:23:14.110 --> 00:23:15.860
What do I mean by open work?

00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:17.770
It's work that we
want to deliver,

00:23:17.770 --> 00:23:20.860
but there's no one
obvious to provide it.

00:23:20.860 --> 00:23:21.910
There's no one.

00:23:21.910 --> 00:23:29.260
So we'll try and buy time
on an overtime basis.

00:23:29.260 --> 00:23:32.000
So we're down here.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:35.842
And if we're lucky,
the overtime--

00:23:35.842 --> 00:23:37.300
there'll be someone
available who's

00:23:37.300 --> 00:23:41.500
willing to work the
overtime for increased pay.

00:23:41.500 --> 00:23:44.920
The negative side of that
is it increases the strain

00:23:44.920 --> 00:23:49.360
on that employee who's working
more hours than he or she was

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:50.620
expecting to.

00:23:50.620 --> 00:23:54.900
That may produce this
negative feedback on absence.

00:23:54.900 --> 00:23:57.970
And I described it
previously as the trade-off

00:23:57.970 --> 00:24:01.690
between how much do I have to
work to get to a certain target

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:02.410
income level?

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:03.740
Well, that's one way
of looking at it.

00:24:03.740 --> 00:24:06.365
But the other way of looking at
it, which is equally realistic,

00:24:06.365 --> 00:24:10.060
is if you're working harder,
that puts more stress

00:24:10.060 --> 00:24:11.020
and strain on the body.

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:13.330
You're more likely to be absent.

00:24:13.330 --> 00:24:16.120
Because there are two ways of
looking at it, which both raise

00:24:16.120 --> 00:24:20.560
the concern about relying
heavily on overtime and what

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:23.000
that will do to absence.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:26.323
Again, over here, if you
can't get the overtime,

00:24:26.323 --> 00:24:27.740
you're going to
be dropping trips.

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:29.960
So reliability suffers.

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:33.447
Negative effect on service
reliability, service quality.

00:24:33.447 --> 00:24:35.030
Presumably, that
will affect ridership

00:24:35.030 --> 00:24:36.650
if it goes on long enough.

00:24:36.650 --> 00:24:38.450
And that will affect
your operating plan,

00:24:38.450 --> 00:24:40.460
because your ridership's down.

00:24:40.460 --> 00:24:43.350
And so there's that
feedback, as well.

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:47.520
So this is sort of another way
of looking at the framework.

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:54.920
Now let's look at the strategic
level in terms of the planning

00:24:54.920 --> 00:24:57.200
process.

00:24:57.200 --> 00:25:05.210
What I've shown here is
a month, as was said--

00:25:05.210 --> 00:25:07.940
four seasons in the MBTA.

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:09.020
Some agencies have more.

00:25:09.020 --> 00:25:10.730
Some have less.

00:25:10.730 --> 00:25:15.060
Winter, spring,
summer, and fall.

00:25:15.060 --> 00:25:20.280
And let's have a hypothetical
workforce hiring scenario,

00:25:20.280 --> 00:25:23.430
where we hire up at the
beginning of each timetable.

00:25:23.430 --> 00:25:25.290
We sort of run
through the timetable.

00:25:25.290 --> 00:25:27.300
And then we hire up
for the beginning

00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:29.080
of the next timetable.

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:30.790
That's sort of the hypothetical.

00:25:30.790 --> 00:25:33.910
That's not unusual.

00:25:33.910 --> 00:25:35.900
But it's not a very
effective way of doing it.

00:25:35.900 --> 00:25:39.260
And what I've tried to explain
here is why that is the case.

00:25:39.260 --> 00:25:48.430
So the bottom bar in this
graph indicates the timetable

00:25:48.430 --> 00:25:50.020
requirements.

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:53.290
So typically, the timetable
requirements for the operating

00:25:53.290 --> 00:26:00.540
plan are pretty similar across
winter, spring, and fall,

00:26:00.540 --> 00:26:02.640
and they're lower in the summer.

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:04.640
Why is that?

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:06.900
No schools, and
people on vacation,

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:08.340
so your demand is
generally down,

00:26:08.340 --> 00:26:13.800
unless it's a very strong summer
tourist place, like Boston.

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:17.760
So that generally means that you
can reduce your operating plan

00:26:17.760 --> 00:26:20.190
requirements in the summer.

00:26:20.190 --> 00:26:21.450
That is a wonderful.

00:26:21.450 --> 00:26:22.500
Why?

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:28.130
Because many drivers would like
to take vacation in the summer,

00:26:28.130 --> 00:26:29.980
OK.

00:26:29.980 --> 00:26:34.830
I mean, unless you're a serious
outdoor skier, ice skater,

00:26:34.830 --> 00:26:36.720
whatever have you in
the winter, you probably

00:26:36.720 --> 00:26:39.660
don't want to take
vacation in the winter

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:43.020
because your children
are still in school.

00:26:43.020 --> 00:26:44.880
Parents want to go
on family vacations

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:46.440
when the weather is decent.

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:52.410
So this cross-hatched area
here is the vacation allocation

00:26:52.410 --> 00:26:54.600
you've made to
fulfill your vacation

00:26:54.600 --> 00:26:56.830
liability over the year.

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:58.830
And so what you
see here is we're

00:26:58.830 --> 00:27:01.860
providing much more
vacation in the summer

00:27:01.860 --> 00:27:04.950
than we are in the
winter, or even

00:27:04.950 --> 00:27:08.160
in the spring and the autumn.

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:08.660
Why?

00:27:08.660 --> 00:27:11.900
That's because our
demand is down,

00:27:11.900 --> 00:27:14.150
but the vacation demand is up.

00:27:14.150 --> 00:27:19.600
So that's a way of
minimizing absenteeism.

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:22.660
Makes our workforce
happy, it's a good thing.

00:27:22.660 --> 00:27:29.180
So this gives us this
profile here about the number

00:27:29.180 --> 00:27:34.580
of people we need to cover the
work and cover the vacations.

00:27:34.580 --> 00:27:38.220
So the only thing we haven't
covered is the absence.

00:27:38.220 --> 00:27:39.975
And we have to cover
