00:28:13.570 --> 00:28:18.700
because people have
made changes and routes.

00:28:18.700 --> 00:28:19.660
There's retraining.

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:21.340
There's training
of new operators.

00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:22.960
So actually, your
required work is

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:25.870
greatest at the end of the
timetable in the last three

00:28:25.870 --> 00:28:28.820
or four weeks.

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:33.550
So that's what this jump here
is, in terms of required work.

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:35.185
However, look at the supply.

00:28:38.350 --> 00:28:40.210
Typically what
happens, is you have

00:28:40.210 --> 00:28:43.710
attrition over the
course of the timetable.

00:28:43.710 --> 00:28:46.470
And you have
increasing absenteeism

00:28:46.470 --> 00:28:47.940
over the course
of the timetable.

00:28:47.940 --> 00:28:48.840
Why?

00:28:48.840 --> 00:28:51.500
Because at the beginning
of the timetable,

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:53.420
people have just
picked that work.

00:28:53.420 --> 00:28:56.450
They sort of want to do it.

00:28:56.450 --> 00:28:57.830
The grass is always greener.

00:28:57.830 --> 00:29:00.590
They're sort of enthusiastic at
the beginning of the timetable.

00:29:00.590 --> 00:29:02.090
They get out there,
and they realize

00:29:02.090 --> 00:29:04.230
it wasn't all it's
cracked up to be.

00:29:04.230 --> 00:29:06.410
And so when they're
not feeling up to it,

00:29:06.410 --> 00:29:11.370
they're more likely to be absent
perhaps, as time wears along.

00:29:11.370 --> 00:29:13.700
And then, towards
the end, they've

00:29:13.700 --> 00:29:16.950
made their new selection of work
for the following timetable.

00:29:16.950 --> 00:29:18.960
OK?

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:24.690
So what this suggests is you
have a surplus of operators

00:29:24.690 --> 00:29:27.120
available at the
beginning of the timetable

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:30.420
and a significant
deficit of operators

00:29:30.420 --> 00:29:33.240
at the end of a timetable.

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:36.550
So you sort of have one day
in the middle of a timetable,

00:29:36.550 --> 00:29:38.470
which is perfect.

00:29:38.470 --> 00:29:41.020
But otherwise, you're off.

00:29:41.020 --> 00:29:44.080
You haven't got this good
balance between the operators

00:29:44.080 --> 00:29:45.990
that you have available
and what you need.

00:29:53.320 --> 00:29:58.850
So clearly doing workforce
hiring every month,

00:29:58.850 --> 00:30:01.450
for instance, is one way
of dealing with this.

00:30:01.450 --> 00:30:07.480
So you can reduce this hump
for training new operators

00:30:07.480 --> 00:30:13.210
and spread it over the whole
period because, in round terms,

00:30:13.210 --> 00:30:16.400
training for an operator
takes about a month

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:18.040
of on-the-road training.

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:22.315
And so you spread that over
the month, over the timetable.

00:30:26.040 --> 00:30:30.110
So going to monthly hiring
makes a lot of sense.

00:30:30.110 --> 00:30:32.630
And again, you
avoid these problems

00:30:32.630 --> 00:30:34.360
having unassigned cover time.

00:30:34.360 --> 00:30:35.860
What that means is
you've got people

00:30:35.860 --> 00:30:39.640
