And typically, as I
said, maybe the period

00:40:36.650 --> 00:40:39.948
of a month, four weeks.

00:40:39.948 --> 00:40:45.410
And vacation allocation for
each period and the vacation

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:49.800
allocation will typically be
over the course of a timetable.

00:40:49.800 --> 00:40:52.260
So what's the average
number of vacation weeks

00:40:52.260 --> 00:40:56.850
we want to provide in the
summer at a particular garage

00:40:56.850 --> 00:40:58.890
or across the whole system?

00:40:58.890 --> 00:41:03.420
We'll provide the same
number of vacation weeks

00:41:03.420 --> 00:41:06.400
for all the bus
system in the MBTA.

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:09.270
And there's someone who's
covering the vacation--

00:41:09.270 --> 00:41:11.760
just is covering the
different vacations

00:41:11.760 --> 00:41:13.680
every week of the timetable.

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:16.110
So we have to have
the same number

00:41:16.110 --> 00:41:18.000
throughout the timetable.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:19.950
OK?

00:41:19.950 --> 00:41:23.970
And the optimal hiring level--
so you get the right number

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:25.590
throughout the year.

00:41:25.590 --> 00:41:30.670
That's sort of what we're
trying to achieve here.

00:41:30.670 --> 00:41:34.150
And the objective is to
minimize the workforce cost,

00:41:34.150 --> 00:41:37.230
which includes the cost
of the schedule runs,

00:41:37.230 --> 00:41:39.480
the costs of the extraboard--
the people who are there

00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:42.030
to cover the absences
and the extra work--

00:41:42.030 --> 00:41:43.375
and the cost of overtime.

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:50.240
And you'll notice there
that I didn't include

00:41:50.240 --> 00:41:52.490
costs of reliability
or unreliability,

00:41:52.490 --> 00:41:56.900
because I'm including
that in the constraint.

00:41:56.900 --> 00:41:58.960
I could have included in
the objective function.

00:41:58.960 --> 00:42:00.938
But I'm including it
in the constraint,

00:42:00.938 --> 00:42:02.480
just because it's
a little bit easier

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:04.160
to conceptualize it that way.

00:42:04.160 --> 00:42:06.710
And we were doing this
work for the MBTA, who

00:42:06.710 --> 00:42:09.740
kind of like to think of
overtime as a constraint.

00:42:09.740 --> 00:42:12.010
Because overtime, as
you're probably aware,

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:16.660
gets a lot of attention in
the medial, in the press.

00:42:16.660 --> 00:42:18.890
You know, "10% of
our budget is being

00:42:18.890 --> 00:42:21.020
spent on overtime for drivers."

00:42:21.020 --> 00:42:23.670
Those are headline
sorts of issues.

00:42:23.670 --> 00:42:25.820
So the MBTA and transit
agency generally

00:42:25.820 --> 00:42:27.950
are sensitive to the
level of overtime.

00:42:27.950 --> 00:42:30.590
That's why I structured
this as a constraint,

00:42:30.590 --> 00:42:34.940
rather than as a
multi-objective function--

00:42:34.940 --> 00:42:38.200
[INAUDIBLE] multiple objectives.

00:42:38.200 --> 00:42:40.330
Constraints we need to
meet-- vacation liability,

00:42:40.330 --> 00:42:45.120
overtime service reliability,
part-time operator constraint--

00:42:45.120 --> 00:42:46.750
sorry.

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:49.120
And any other policy
constraints that we want to

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:52.780
can be included in this
optimization problem.

00:42:52.780 --> 00:42:58.720
And the reliability model that
we have is basically this.

00:42:58.720 --> 00:43:01.590
So what this is saying
is we have open work.

00:43:01.590 --> 00:43:06.230
What open work means is we
have work we want to do.

00:43:06.230 --> 00:43:09.310
We don't have anyone who's
going to be willing to do it

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.050
without paying overtime.

00:43:11.050 --> 00:43:13.100
That's what I mean by open work.

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:15.010
It's work that wasn't
a regularly scheduled

00:43:15.010 --> 00:43:17.620
employee available to cover.

00:43:17.620 --> 00:43:19.720
So overtime is available.

00:43:19.720 --> 00:43:25.990
If an operator is available
and willing to work time,

00:43:25.990 --> 00:43:27.550
you come down here.

00:43:27.550 --> 00:43:28.930
And overtime is worked.

00:43:28.930 --> 00:43:30.610
That may produce more absence.

00:43:30.610 --> 00:43:34.120
May have those negative
feedback effects.

00:43:34.120 --> 00:43:38.200
But at least you've delivered
the service that day.

00:43:38.200 --> 00:43:41.300
If there's no operator
available or there's

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:44.033
no operator willing to work the
overtime, you drop the trips.

00:43:44.033 --> 00:43:46.158
And you've got a reliability
problem on your hands.

00:43:51.043 --> 00:43:52.960
Don't worry about the
individual points there.

00:43:52.960 --> 00:44:02.360
But this is showing for the
bus network on the MBTA,

00:44:02.360 --> 00:44:05.202
on the x-axis, the open work.

00:44:05.202 --> 00:44:09.760
This is for a particular
timetable, system-wide

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:13.510
for the bus, and the
number of missed trip hours

00:44:13.510 --> 00:44:15.200
that were incurred that day.

00:44:15.200 --> 00:44:19.930
So each point here
represents a day of operation

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:22.340
on the MBTA bus system.

00:44:22.340 --> 00:44:27.710
And so this particular day,
you had close to 300 hours

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.630
of open work.

00:44:29.630 --> 00:44:34.825
And you dropped close
to 150 hours of service.

00:44:37.550 --> 00:44:41.260
And if you do an OLS
regression on this,

00:44:41.260 --> 00:44:45.370
this was the best fit we got.

00:44:45.370 --> 00:44:48.850
So that means for every
100 hours of open work

00:44:48.850 --> 00:44:54.810
at the time we did this
analysis that you wanted to get,

00:44:54.810 --> 00:44:57.390
you were only able to get 72.

00:44:57.390 --> 00:45:01.370
And you wound up dropping
28 hours of service.

00:45:01.370 --> 00:45:03.140
That is pretty tough.

00:45:03.140 --> 00:45:06.570
That's actually
really quite bad.

00:45:06.570 --> 00:45:08.790
By comparison purposes,
I've done other work

00:45:08.790 --> 00:45:12.100
in Montreal,
Ottawa, and Toronto,

00:45:12.100 --> 00:45:16.230
which are pretty good, more or
less, east coast properties.

00:45:16.230 --> 00:45:20.050
In Canada, they're
never more than 10%.

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:24.840
So there's something not
being done very efficiently

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:29.380
in the way the MBTA
covers their overtime.

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:30.960
And I think part
of this is probably

00:45:30.960 --> 00:45:36.390
over-reliance on seniority,
again, and probably not

00:45:36.390 --> 00:45:38.130
doing enough advance planning.

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:47.370
And what do I mean by relying
too heavily on seniority?

00:45:47.370 --> 00:45:50.820
How many phone calls do you make
to the most senior operator who

00:45:50.820 --> 00:45:53.550
might be available before
you say, he or she isn't

00:45:53.550 --> 00:45:54.960
going to do this
work, and you go

00:45:54.960 --> 00:45:57.560
to the next person on the list?

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:59.590
And how much advance
planning do you

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:03.850
do to make sure that you've
got a set of operators who

00:46:03.850 --> 00:46:07.980
are really going to be available
if you have a need for them

00:46:07.980 --> 00:46:10.490
at 9 o'clock tomorrow morning?

00:46:10.490 --> 00:46:13.300
Those are the things that you
could do to try and reduce

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:17.860
this 28% missed trips to 5%
or 10% missed trips, which

00:46:17.860 --> 00:46:21.692
would be a much better situation
for everyone concerned.

00:46:24.530 --> 00:46:26.970
So this is the MBTA
case study again.

00:46:26.970 --> 00:46:30.830
Bear in mind that this
was basically mid 1990s.

00:46:30.830 --> 00:46:31.810
So it's 20 years ago.

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:36.850
But also, believe
me, nothing much

00:46:36.850 --> 00:46:38.980
has changed in this
regard at the MBTA.

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:41.380
I'm not saying nothing's
changed in the MBTA

00:46:41.380 --> 00:46:43.480
in any regard over
the last 20 years.

00:46:43.480 --> 00:46:47.850
But certainly in this regard,
nothing much has changed.

00:46:47.850 --> 00:46:50.170
And I think there are still
some of the same problems

00:46:50.170 --> 00:46:53.350
that I'll talk about here
still in existence, which

00:46:53.350 --> 00:46:55.720
is sad for me to admit
because, obviously, I

00:46:55.720 --> 00:46:57.200
was trying to help them--

00:46:57.200 --> 00:47:00.200
didn't succeed.

00:47:00.200 --> 00:47:02.950
So at that point, the
part-time workforce

00:47:02.950 --> 00:47:05.980
was sized to about 40% of
the full-time workforce.

00:47:05.980 --> 00:47:09.930
That's a little bit
lower now, I believe.

00:47:09.930 --> 00:47:14.950
There's a large variability
in required work hours.

00:47:14.950 --> 00:47:16.550
So what do I mean by that?

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:19.350
The mean daily
absence and extra work

00:47:19.350 --> 00:47:22.200
required-- this is apart
from the timetable.

00:47:22.200 --> 00:47:24.540
So this is shuttling
service when

00:47:24.540 --> 00:47:29.730
you get a line down
for signaling problem

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:35.530
or disabled train or whatever it
is, or fatality on the tracks.

00:47:35.530 --> 00:47:37.650
The mean daily
absence and extra work

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:40.020
for the whole MBTA
bus system was

00:47:40.020 --> 00:47:44.340
1,250 hours on a daily basis.

00:47:44.340 --> 00:47:47.220
And the standard deviation
of that was 290 hours.

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:50.370
AUDIENCE: What percent
of that is total hours?

00:47:50.370 --> 00:47:51.750
NIGEL HM WILSON: It's coming up.

00:47:55.398 --> 00:47:56.940
I'm getting into it
in a few minutes.

00:47:56.940 --> 00:48:01.517
But round figure's 10%.

00:48:01.517 --> 00:48:02.100
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:48:02.100 --> 00:48:03.380
NIGEL HM WILSON:
It's pretty high.

00:48:03.380 --> 00:48:04.450
That's not just absence.

00:48:04.450 --> 00:48:07.090
It doesn't include extra work.

00:48:07.090 --> 00:48:07.803
OK?

00:48:07.803 --> 00:48:10.220
AUDIENCE: But it does
include sick leave, as well?

00:48:10.220 --> 00:48:10.670
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

00:48:10.670 --> 00:48:11.070
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:48:11.070 --> 00:48:11.490
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

00:48:11.490 --> 00:48:12.100
AUDIENCE: Any kind of absence.

00:48:12.100 --> 00:48:12.975
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

00:48:12.975 --> 00:48:14.420
Any sort of absence, exactly.

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:17.125
So it's not in any
sense absenteeism.

00:48:17.125 --> 00:48:18.500
It's the amount
of extra work you

00:48:18.500 --> 00:48:22.625
have to do beyond what's
the scheduled work,

00:48:22.625 --> 00:48:25.800
the scheduled operating plan.

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:29.750
But anyway, it's quite large,
and it's very variable.

00:48:29.750 --> 00:48:32.170
So it is highly stochastic.

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:35.310
Now, these figures
were from 1996.

00:48:35.310 --> 00:48:38.740
And so the numbers will
have changed significantly

00:48:38.740 --> 00:48:40.190
over the last 20 years.

00:48:40.190 --> 00:48:42.770
But the relative
ratio of the numbers

00:48:42.770 --> 00:48:44.650
in the different
columns and cells

00:48:44.650 --> 00:48:48.380
has not changed significantly
in the last 20 years.

00:48:48.380 --> 00:48:49.780
So what this is saying--

00:48:49.780 --> 00:48:56.627
what we're showing here is the
driver cost per platform hour.

00:49:00.370 --> 00:49:04.360
And so this includes
the wage rate

00:49:04.360 --> 00:49:09.080
and benefits-- fixed and
variable fringe benefits.

00:49:09.080 --> 00:49:18.100
So an hour of overtime worked
by a driver at that time

00:49:18.100 --> 00:49:19.930
was around $30 an hour.

00:49:23.710 --> 00:49:27.310
So sorry, the first
row is the wage rate.

00:49:27.310 --> 00:49:30.040
The second row is the full cost.

00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:33.550
So the difference here is the
benefits that are included,

00:49:33.550 --> 00:49:38.000
and the productivity changes
between overtime, part-time,

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:39.010
and full-timers.

00:49:39.010 --> 00:49:43.060
So for overtime, you get
a very small benefit load

00:49:43.060 --> 00:49:47.570
because most of the benefits are
covered through their base job,

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:48.070
OK.

00:49:48.070 --> 00:49:50.980
So the marginal cost
of overtime work

00:49:50.980 --> 00:49:53.530
in terms of the benefit
load is quite small,

00:49:53.530 --> 00:49:56.470
in the order of less than 10%--

00:49:56.470 --> 00:49:58.590
or just about 10% of this.

00:49:58.590 --> 00:50:01.570
Whereas for part-timers
and full-timers,

00:50:01.570 --> 00:50:06.200
full-timers get somewhat
greater benefits.

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:08.650
So it's a significant increment.

00:50:08.650 --> 00:50:11.170
So if you just scan
across here, this

00:50:11.170 --> 00:50:13.990
gives you the straight,
direct comparison

00:50:13.990 --> 00:50:17.590
between the cost of an hour of
work produced on an overtime

00:50:17.590 --> 00:50:21.400
basis by a full-timer
or by a part-timer.

00:50:21.400 --> 00:50:25.660
And in round terms,
you say, well,

00:50:25.660 --> 00:50:29.290
if it's 40% part-timer,
60% full-timer, as the mix

00:50:29.290 --> 00:50:34.630
of workforce, versus $32.72
for an overtime, it's a wash.

00:50:34.630 --> 00:50:37.070
It's basically the same.

00:50:37.070 --> 00:50:37.770
OK.

00:50:37.770 --> 00:50:41.950
So strictly in terms of cost,
it doesn't really matter.

00:50:41.950 --> 00:50:44.540
It matters a lot if you
have far too many people.

00:50:44.540 --> 00:50:48.150
But it doesn't matter too
much in terms of the cost

00:50:48.150 --> 00:50:50.390
if you have about
the right number

00:50:50.390 --> 00:50:53.160
or slightly less
than that number.

00:50:53.160 --> 00:50:56.520
If you have a lot
less than that number,

00:50:56.520 --> 00:50:59.220
the short-run financial
costs won't change,

00:50:59.220 --> 00:51:01.230
but you'll have
reliability problems

00:51:01.230 --> 00:51:04.570
because you won't be
able to get the overtime.

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:07.500
However, what we really
should be looking at

00:51:07.500 --> 00:51:12.570
is the marginal cost of the
last person on the cover list.

00:51:12.570 --> 00:51:15.540
That's where we're making
the marginal decision about

00:51:15.540 --> 00:51:17.610
whether we want to increase
the cover list by 1

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:20.730
or decrease it by 1 or
hold it where it is.

00:51:20.730 --> 00:51:24.830
So if the last person
on the cover list

00:51:24.830 --> 00:51:29.930
is being used 50% of
the time, then you're

00:51:29.930 --> 00:51:34.720
making a trade off between
$32.72 for an overtime hour

00:51:34.720 --> 00:51:41.170
versus $69.56 for the marginal
person on the cover list.

00:51:43.850 --> 00:51:50.110
OK, so what a critical issue
is, in terms of any of you guys

00:51:50.110 --> 00:51:51.850
doing analysis for
transit agency,

00:51:51.850 --> 00:51:55.780
be it JR-East or the MBTA or
whatever it is, in this area,

00:51:55.780 --> 00:51:59.320
you really want to look at what
the distribution of the costs

00:51:59.320 --> 00:52:02.410
are of the cover list.

00:52:02.410 --> 00:52:06.330
And a good proxy
for that is who's

00:52:06.330 --> 00:52:09.600
picking the work
on the cover list.

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:11.300
If it's the most
senior operators who

00:52:11.300 --> 00:52:13.460
are picking the work
on the cover list,

00:52:13.460 --> 00:52:15.230
that means that's
pretty easy work.

00:52:18.020 --> 00:52:21.050
If the senior operators are
not picking the cover list

00:52:21.050 --> 00:52:24.380
and it's being left to the
junior people on the seniority

00:52:24.380 --> 00:52:29.010
list, that means the senior
operators want to avoid it

00:52:29.010 --> 00:52:31.770
because it's difficult work.

00:52:31.770 --> 00:52:35.130
So that's a sort of
very simple shortcut--

00:52:35.130 --> 00:52:38.020
do we have an oversized cover
list or an undersized cover

00:52:38.020 --> 00:52:38.520
list?

00:52:38.520 --> 00:52:41.730
Look at who's picking that
work on the cover list.

00:52:41.730 --> 00:52:44.980
Is it very senior
operators or not?

00:52:44.980 --> 00:52:46.997
Any questions on this?

00:52:46.997 --> 00:52:49.330
AUDIENCE: So cover lists--
are those people who come in,

00:52:49.330 --> 00:52:50.670
and they're sort of waiting
to go on a [INAUDIBLE]??

00:52:50.670 --> 00:52:51.100
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yeah.

00:52:51.100 --> 00:52:51.196
Yeah.

00:52:51.196 --> 00:52:52.240
AUDIENCE: They're not people
who are sitting at home,

00:52:52.240 --> 00:52:52.780
waiting for a phone call.

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:53.947
NIGEL HM WILSON: No, no, no.

00:52:53.947 --> 00:52:55.713
They're in the garage--

00:52:55.713 --> 00:52:57.130
maybe playing cards
in the garage.

00:52:57.130 --> 00:52:58.540
But they're in the garage,
and they're available.

00:52:58.540 --> 00:52:59.037
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:52:59.037 --> 00:52:59.870
NIGEL HM WILSON: OK.

00:53:03.020 --> 00:53:06.020
OK, so I'm not going to
go through the model.

00:53:06.020 --> 00:53:10.670
Again, I'm happy to give you
the papers and theses on this.

00:53:10.670 --> 00:53:13.453
One of these theses was done
by Haris Koutsopoulos, who

00:53:13.453 --> 00:53:14.620
many of you know quite well.

00:53:14.620 --> 00:53:17.450
He's a senior faculty
member at Northeastern.

00:53:17.450 --> 00:53:21.560
Another of the theses was
done by Yoram Shiftan,

00:53:21.560 --> 00:53:26.137
who was entertaining me in
Israel just three days ago.

00:53:26.137 --> 00:53:28.470
So there's some very good
work that's been done on this.

00:53:28.470 --> 00:53:34.838
But the model that
came out of this--

00:53:34.838 --> 00:53:36.380
I'm going to go show
you some results

00:53:36.380 --> 00:53:40.840
and talk about what they mean.

00:53:40.840 --> 00:53:45.913
What this is showing is,
under different scenarios,

00:53:45.913 --> 00:53:47.330
the number of
full-time operators,

00:53:47.330 --> 00:53:51.950
the number of part-time
operators that produce

00:53:51.950 --> 00:53:57.230
the optimal solution,
the overtime as a percent

00:53:57.230 --> 00:54:01.810
of the full cost--

00:54:01.810 --> 00:54:06.070
the full cost, $96.4 million
in this case, per year.

00:54:09.450 --> 00:54:12.932
Sorry, that's the regular
cost, regular time cost.

00:54:12.932 --> 00:54:13.890
It's the overtime cost.

00:54:13.890 --> 00:54:15.810
You add them up, and
you get the total cost--

00:54:15.810 --> 00:54:17.370
$97.8 here.

00:54:17.370 --> 00:54:21.230
And this is adding
different constraints.

00:54:21.230 --> 00:54:25.720
So the base case, without any
constraints beyond vacation

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:29.720
or liability-- the things that
we've already talked about--

00:54:29.720 --> 00:54:42.430
are that the cost of the
MBTA bus drivers should be--

00:54:42.430 --> 00:54:48.710
these are 1996 dollars
again-- but $98 million.

00:54:48.710 --> 00:54:52.220
And the reliability,
given 1.5% of the time

00:54:52.220 --> 00:54:53.870
has to be worked on
overtime, and given

00:54:53.870 --> 00:54:56.360
the way they manage their
overtime, which is not

00:54:56.360 --> 00:54:59.540
very good, not
very well, they'll

00:54:59.540 --> 00:55:03.320
be dropping about
0.4% of the trips--

00:55:03.320 --> 00:55:06.770
4 trips out of every 1,000.

00:55:06.770 --> 00:55:09.450
That was their existing
level of unreliability

00:55:09.450 --> 00:55:12.920
in terms of dropping service.

00:55:12.920 --> 00:55:14.720
So that's the base case numbers.

00:55:14.720 --> 00:55:17.340
You could then add
different constraints.

00:55:17.340 --> 00:55:20.570
If you add a constant
hiring constraint, which

00:55:20.570 --> 00:55:25.840
means that we hire the same
number of operators every month

00:55:25.840 --> 00:55:27.460
over the course
of the year and we

00:55:27.460 --> 00:55:30.080
don't allow it to vary
from month to month,

00:55:30.080 --> 00:55:31.640
what does that do?

00:55:31.640 --> 00:55:34.480
It makes it easier for
the human resources folks.

00:55:34.480 --> 00:55:36.540
It makes it easier for
the training people,

00:55:36.540 --> 00:55:38.290
because they know what
their load is going

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:40.460
to be throughout the year.

00:55:40.460 --> 00:55:43.860
And in fact, you can incorporate
that single constraint

00:55:43.860 --> 00:55:48.790
with zero impact on the
budget or reliability.

00:55:48.790 --> 00:55:50.670
So the solution is
exactly the same.

00:55:50.670 --> 00:55:52.680
We've just juggled
vacation liability

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:54.760
between different periods.

00:55:54.760 --> 00:55:57.410
OK?

00:55:57.410 --> 00:56:00.980
If we wanted to have a
constant vacation as a policy

00:56:00.980 --> 00:56:03.560
in the organization, we
add that as a constraint--

00:56:03.560 --> 00:56:06.960
so the same month vacation
throughout the year--

00:56:06.960 --> 00:56:11.570
then that would result in
about an almost $2 million

00:56:11.570 --> 00:56:18.020
increase in the total cost
of the MBTA bus drivers.

00:56:18.020 --> 00:56:20.240
We'd have less overtime.

00:56:20.240 --> 00:56:22.850
And so our reliability
would improve

00:56:22.850 --> 00:56:26.330
to dropping 2 trips
out of every 1,000,

00:56:26.330 --> 00:56:28.700
rather than 4 trips
out of every 1,000.

00:56:28.700 --> 00:56:31.460
And if we included in them
both the constant hiring

00:56:31.460 --> 00:56:33.715
and vacation, which I
don't think you'd want to,

00:56:33.715 --> 00:56:35.090
but this is just
to show what you

00:56:35.090 --> 00:56:37.280
can do with this
sort of model, then

00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:41.180
that would increase the budget
by an additional $1.5 million

00:56:41.180 --> 00:56:42.580
a year.

00:56:42.580 --> 00:56:46.670
And because you'd be
relying less on overtime,

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:49.140
you'd be having even
more reliable service.

00:56:49.140 --> 00:56:53.780
So it gives the MBTA managers
a sense of the trade offs here,

00:56:53.780 --> 00:56:57.440
but between the size of the
workforce optimally structured

00:56:57.440 --> 00:57:01.184
over the course of the year
and reliability and overtime.

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:06.900
One different set
of results here.

00:57:06.900 --> 00:57:09.420
This is showing,
OK, so what happens

00:57:09.420 --> 00:57:13.780
if we change the level of
the overtime constraint?

00:57:13.780 --> 00:57:21.450
So the base case here is
1.5% time as a constraint.

00:57:21.450 --> 00:57:24.870
If we just eliminated the
overtime constraint completely

00:57:24.870 --> 00:57:29.630
and said, just choose
the amount of overtime

00:57:29.630 --> 00:57:32.990
that gives you the
minimal cost solution,

00:57:32.990 --> 00:57:38.860
then your overtime costs would
be close to $12 million a year.

00:57:38.860 --> 00:57:41.590
And that would enable you
to save about $1.3 million

00:57:41.590 --> 00:57:44.050
per year on the
overall budget, because

00:57:44.050 --> 00:57:49.610
of the relative costs of
overtime versus regular work.

00:57:49.610 --> 00:57:54.110
However, your reliability would
go to hell in a hand basket.

00:57:54.110 --> 00:57:56.405
And you'd be dropping 3
trips out of every 100--

00:57:56.405 --> 00:57:58.550
3 hours of service
out of every 100.

00:57:58.550 --> 00:58:00.230
And probably, this
is much better

00:58:00.230 --> 00:58:02.540
than it would really
be if you did that.

00:58:02.540 --> 00:58:05.630
Because this is not a
linear function, OK.

00:58:05.630 --> 00:58:07.380
You're going to have
more and more trouble

00:58:07.380 --> 00:58:09.005
covering those trips
and getting people

00:58:09.005 --> 00:58:11.820
to agree to work overtime if
there's so much overtime being

00:58:11.820 --> 00:58:13.990
asked of the workforce.

00:58:13.990 --> 00:58:16.592
So this is a gross
underestimate.

00:58:16.592 --> 00:58:21.370
But if you looked at 5%,
which is still pretty high,

00:58:21.370 --> 00:58:26.700
then you'd save, in theory,
about $800,000 a year--

00:58:26.700 --> 00:58:28.470
less than $1 million a year.

00:58:28.470 --> 00:58:33.720
And your reliability would
decrease significantly

00:58:33.720 --> 00:58:36.900
from dropping 4 trips
out of every 1,000

00:58:36.900 --> 00:58:43.410
to dropping 120 trips
out of every 1,000--

00:58:43.410 --> 00:58:45.980
no, 12-- from 4 to 12.

00:58:49.730 --> 00:58:53.480
And then if you tighten
the overtime constraint

00:58:53.480 --> 00:58:57.420
for whatever reason, then this
is what it would cost you.

00:58:57.420 --> 00:59:00.870
It would cost you about half
a million dollars a year.

00:59:00.870 --> 00:59:04.460
And again, you get some
improvement in reliability.

00:59:04.460 --> 00:59:08.210
So these are the sort of
uses of the model that you

00:59:08.210 --> 00:59:12.560
can use to inform management
decisions about how you

00:59:12.560 --> 00:59:15.010
structure your hiring
process and training process

00:59:15.010 --> 00:59:16.137
and extraboard size.

00:59:19.150 --> 00:59:19.650
OK.

00:59:19.650 --> 00:59:22.200
That's all I want to say
on the strategic level.

00:59:22.200 --> 00:59:24.420
Any questions?

00:59:24.420 --> 00:59:25.626
Yes.

00:59:25.626 --> 00:59:28.494
AUDIENCE: Do you have a
sense of how difficult it is

00:59:28.494 --> 00:59:34.150
or how costly it is to hire
additional, new drivers?

00:59:34.150 --> 00:59:35.140
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

00:59:35.140 --> 00:59:36.400
Yes.

00:59:36.400 --> 00:59:38.890
So there is a training period.

00:59:38.890 --> 00:59:41.320
The MBTA, since
Fred was Secretary,

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:46.690
has had a lottery process for
selection of new employees.

00:59:46.690 --> 00:59:48.910
And every agency,
including the MBTA,

00:59:48.910 --> 00:59:50.650
has a pretty rigorous
testing procedure

00:59:50.650 --> 00:59:53.920
you have to go through to get
to the point of being hired.

00:59:53.920 --> 00:59:56.020
You then go through training,
the criminal records

00:59:56.020 --> 00:59:59.530
check, all sorts of checks
before the training begins.

00:59:59.530 --> 01:00:02.045
And then the training--

01:00:02.045 --> 01:00:05.410
I'm trying to remember, I don't
have it on top of a head--

01:00:05.410 --> 01:00:10.210
I think that the
total training is

01:00:10.210 --> 01:00:12.610
in the order of six
weeks, which includes

01:00:12.610 --> 01:00:14.410
getting your commercial
driver's licenses,

01:00:14.410 --> 01:00:16.960
as we talked about earlier.

01:00:16.960 --> 01:00:21.400
So you've got a certain amount
of advance planning in here.

01:00:21.400 --> 01:00:24.890
You can't decide today, I
want to have more people

01:00:24.890 --> 01:00:26.442
on the driver
workforce tomorrow.

01:00:26.442 --> 01:00:27.400
It's not going to work.

01:00:27.400 --> 01:00:30.280
So that's why you need to
have a strategic view of this.

01:00:30.280 --> 01:00:31.115
Yes?

01:00:31.115 --> 01:00:35.075
AUDIENCE: Does this model
capture the behavioral feedback

01:00:35.075 --> 01:00:35.882
loop?

01:00:35.882 --> 01:00:37.090
NIGEL HM WILSON: It does not.

01:00:37.090 --> 01:00:38.440
So that was separate work.

01:00:38.440 --> 01:00:41.040
And we did look at that.

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:43.560
But it's not in the
results I presented.

01:00:43.560 --> 01:00:45.490
Though, as I said,
Yoram Shiftan looked

01:00:45.490 --> 01:00:49.630
at feedback effect between
if you provide more overtime,

01:00:49.630 --> 01:00:52.170
what does that do to absence?

01:00:52.170 --> 01:00:55.200
And what he found
was, it's variable.

01:00:55.200 --> 01:00:58.170
For some operators, there
is a feedback effect.

01:00:58.170 --> 01:01:02.650
But it's not as strong
as you might expect, OK.

01:01:02.650 --> 01:01:04.420
So the MBTA management,
for instance,

01:01:04.420 --> 01:01:09.880
was pretty convinced this
was really a serious issue.

01:01:09.880 --> 01:01:11.450
It wasn't, in our analysis.

01:01:11.450 --> 01:01:14.110
But there is a feedback effect.

01:01:14.110 --> 01:01:17.330
It's not reflected in here.

01:01:17.330 --> 01:01:18.810
Yeah, Scott.

01:01:18.810 --> 01:01:20.310
AUDIENCE: Earlier,
you said you look

01:01:20.310 --> 01:01:24.938
at the seniority of the
extraboards that are taking

01:01:24.938 --> 01:01:25.980
work from the cover list.

01:01:25.980 --> 01:01:26.370
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

01:01:26.370 --> 01:01:27.950
AUDIENCE: And you said
it's approximately

01:01:27.950 --> 01:01:29.410
more than the work
that's desirable, right?

01:01:29.410 --> 01:01:29.810
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

01:01:29.810 --> 01:01:30.810
AUDIENCE: The more senior
person takes the work

01:01:30.810 --> 01:01:31.685
from the [INAUDIBLE]?

01:01:31.685 --> 01:01:32.810
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes, yes.

01:01:32.810 --> 01:01:35.310
AUDIENCE: And I didn't quite
get the implication there

01:01:35.310 --> 01:01:38.680
for the amount of
work, [INAUDIBLE]..

01:01:38.680 --> 01:01:40.400
NIGEL HM WILSON: OK.

01:01:40.400 --> 01:01:40.900
So yeah.

01:01:40.900 --> 01:01:44.020
So if the most
senior operators--

01:01:44.020 --> 01:01:46.575
who can pick anything--
are picking the extraboard,

01:01:46.575 --> 01:01:47.950
that means you
don't have to work

01:01:47.950 --> 01:01:49.300
very hard in the extraboard.

01:01:49.300 --> 01:01:51.880
The extraboard is
probably too large.

01:01:51.880 --> 01:01:52.380
OK.

01:01:52.380 --> 01:01:54.570
That's the simple proxy.

01:01:54.570 --> 01:01:57.810
Similarly, if the
most senior operators

01:01:57.810 --> 01:02:02.520
are picking certain duties
in a garage in terms

01:02:02.520 --> 01:02:06.060
of the types of shifts
and the days they work,

01:02:06.060 --> 01:02:10.180
that's a good proxy for what's
easy, what's not so easy.

01:02:10.180 --> 01:02:12.860
That's not to say
senior operators aren't

01:02:12.860 --> 01:02:13.650
highly motivated.

01:02:13.650 --> 01:02:14.150
They are.

01:02:14.150 --> 01:02:16.360
But they also have their
own self-interest at heart.

01:02:16.360 --> 01:02:18.840
They don't necessarily want to
be on a dangerous, difficult

01:02:18.840 --> 01:02:20.448
route to operate.

01:02:20.448 --> 01:02:22.490
Now, the problem here,
which Fred will get into I

01:02:22.490 --> 01:02:26.142
think next week, in terms
of the way the US transit

01:02:26.142 --> 01:02:28.100
industry operates-- there
are lots of problems.

01:02:28.100 --> 01:02:31.040
But one of the problems in
terms of the way the US transit

01:02:31.040 --> 01:02:35.010
industry operates, compared
with European industry,

01:02:35.010 --> 01:02:39.280
is they rely very
heavily on seniority.

01:02:39.280 --> 01:02:41.890
So what does that mean?

01:02:41.890 --> 01:02:45.580
It means the least
capable drivers, who

01:02:45.580 --> 01:02:47.330
are the people who
are new in the job

01:02:47.330 --> 01:02:49.500
and haven't got a
lot of experience,

01:02:49.500 --> 01:02:52.630
have the most
difficult assignments.

01:02:52.630 --> 01:02:56.550
That's almost
certainly not optimal.

01:02:56.550 --> 01:03:01.430
So it means you have
very poor drivers,

01:03:01.430 --> 01:03:03.110
in terms of not
their capability,

01:03:03.110 --> 01:03:05.630
but where they are on
the learning curve,

01:03:05.630 --> 01:03:08.860
driving very difficult routes.

01:03:08.860 --> 01:03:12.550
And the European
approach to this

01:03:12.550 --> 01:03:16.130
is typically to have
a rotating roster, OK.

01:03:18.690 --> 01:03:23.720
And again, in the
US transit industry,

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:26.600
one of the main benefits
of more seniority

01:03:26.600 --> 01:03:31.470
for a particular individual
is you get to pick your work,

01:03:31.470 --> 01:03:35.010
and you get to pick
your vacation time.

01:03:35.010 --> 01:03:36.897
So if you get to 10
years at the MBTA,

01:03:36.897 --> 01:03:38.980
perhaps you never have to
work weekends unless you

01:03:38.980 --> 01:03:42.180
particularly want it,
which you often won't.

01:03:42.180 --> 01:03:48.150
Whereas in most
European systems,

01:03:48.150 --> 01:03:50.670
you're assigned to a
roster that rotates.

01:03:50.670 --> 01:03:53.610
So you will all go through
the same experience

01:03:53.610 --> 01:03:57.100
over the course of two months.

01:03:57.100 --> 01:03:59.023
I don't know how
JR-East does it, Kenji.

01:03:59.023 --> 01:04:00.190
AUDIENCE: Similar to Europe.

01:04:00.190 --> 01:04:01.648
NIGEL HM WILSON:
Similar to Europe.

01:04:01.648 --> 01:04:04.405
That's really the
dominant model elsewhere

01:04:04.405 --> 01:04:05.950
that I'm familiar with.

01:04:05.950 --> 01:04:09.670
There are trade offs in this.

01:04:09.670 --> 01:04:13.930
So one of the trade
offs is that if you

01:04:13.930 --> 01:04:17.560
use that as your main
motivation for keeping people

01:04:17.560 --> 01:04:18.715
on the workforce--

01:04:18.715 --> 01:04:20.590
you want to keep your
good operators working,

01:04:20.590 --> 01:04:21.923
you don't have to replace them--

01:04:24.530 --> 01:04:29.860
you can either pay a
wage rate incentive

01:04:29.860 --> 01:04:35.960
for longevity, which is more
common in other agencies

01:04:35.960 --> 01:04:37.110
around the world.

01:04:37.110 --> 01:04:39.070
But it's not very
common in the US.

01:04:39.070 --> 01:04:45.680
And so you progress from the
entry level wage in the MBTA

01:04:45.680 --> 01:04:49.690
to the top level
in about two years.

01:04:49.690 --> 01:04:54.520
OK, and that's not unusual
in the US transit industry.

01:04:54.520 --> 01:04:57.670
And so because that is
such a minimal incentive

01:04:57.670 --> 01:05:01.270
to hang around for
20 years, you want

01:05:01.270 --> 01:05:02.800
to provide other incentives.

01:05:02.800 --> 01:05:07.090
And so seniority, picking your
work, picking your vacation,

01:05:07.090 --> 01:05:09.460
is the way the US transit
industry has followed this.

01:05:09.460 --> 01:05:11.348
Gabriel, you were going
to make a comment.

01:05:11.348 --> 01:05:13.890
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: It's
a half-comment, half-question.

01:05:13.890 --> 01:05:14.100
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yeah.

01:05:14.100 --> 01:05:15.517
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
But when

01:05:15.517 --> 01:05:17.362
we discussed crew
scheduling, we briefly

01:05:17.362 --> 01:05:19.603
touched on rostering
and differences

01:05:19.603 --> 01:05:21.520
between North American
and European practices.

01:05:21.520 --> 01:05:21.860
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

01:05:21.860 --> 01:05:23.860
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
And well, part of that

01:05:23.860 --> 01:05:29.040
was that in European practice,
rostering is done sometimes

01:05:29.040 --> 01:05:31.930
with some help of
alarm or helping

01:05:31.930 --> 01:05:35.283
them to make the different
rosters as even as possible.

01:05:35.283 --> 01:05:36.241
NIGEL HM WILSON: Right.

01:05:36.241 --> 01:05:37.658
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
And that

01:05:37.658 --> 01:05:40.295
is slightly different
from picking them.

01:05:40.295 --> 01:05:41.170
NIGEL HM WILSON: Yes.

01:05:41.170 --> 01:05:42.390
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Right, so in North American,

01:05:42.390 --> 01:05:44.160
these rosters are
formed by people,

01:05:44.160 --> 01:05:48.230
but then they assemble the
rosters from crew schedules.

01:05:48.230 --> 01:05:49.293
Is that correct?

01:05:49.293 --> 01:05:50.710
NIGEL HM WILSON:
Well, the roster,

01:05:50.710 --> 01:05:56.110
as I'm describing the roster,
is the rotation, if any,

01:05:56.110 --> 01:05:58.510
of the work that's
done among individuals

01:05:58.510 --> 01:06:01.390
over the course of a period,
maybe a timetable or two

01:06:01.390 --> 01:06:03.070
months.

01:06:03.070 --> 01:06:05.110
If you have a
rotating roster, that

01:06:05.110 --> 01:06:06.490
means everyone in
this group goes

01:06:06.490 --> 01:06:09.490
through the same set of
driving responsibilities

01:06:09.490 --> 01:06:12.100
over the course of a two-month
period or a timetable.

01:06:14.820 --> 01:06:18.910
In the US transit industry case,
you don't have any rotation.

01:06:18.910 --> 01:06:20.590
You don't even have a roster.

01:06:20.590 --> 01:06:25.890
So you're there, you do
the same trip every day

01:06:25.890 --> 01:06:27.330
if you show up for work.

01:06:27.330 --> 01:06:31.440
If you don't show up for
work, you don't do the duty.

01:06:31.440 --> 01:06:37.740
So it's a trade off.

01:06:37.740 --> 01:06:40.860
Personally-- maybe it's
my European roots--

01:06:40.860 --> 01:06:44.200
I kind of tend to prefer a
European approach to this

01:06:44.200 --> 01:06:46.960
than the US approach to this.

01:06:46.960 --> 01:06:47.460
OK.

01:06:47.460 --> 01:06:51.280
Let me quickly jump
into the tactical level.

01:06:51.280 --> 01:06:54.540
So here, we're going
into the summer timetable

01:06:54.540 --> 01:06:57.890
the MBTA in about
a month's time.

01:06:57.890 --> 01:06:59.700
And so we'll be deciding.

01:06:59.700 --> 01:07:04.700
We know how many drivers
we have on the property.

01:07:04.700 --> 01:07:07.850
What we're deciding
now is when to assign

01:07:07.850 --> 01:07:11.060
the work on a daily basis
and how many operators

01:07:11.060 --> 01:07:17.270
to provide to Lynn versus Quincy
versus Arborway versus Cabot--

01:07:17.270 --> 01:07:20.210
the different depots
in the system.

01:07:20.210 --> 01:07:23.380
And again, so we're
allocating the extra staff,

01:07:23.380 --> 01:07:29.320
these floaters, by garage
and by day of week.

01:07:29.320 --> 01:07:31.510
And so we want to
know the absence level

01:07:31.510 --> 01:07:36.240
on a more detailed basis here.

01:07:36.240 --> 01:07:39.840
We have basically the same
sort of issues and concerns,

01:07:39.840 --> 01:07:43.770
just at a more detailed
level of analysis.

01:07:43.770 --> 01:07:46.290
And we can either use a
heuristic or optimization

01:07:46.290 --> 01:07:47.160
for this.

01:07:47.160 --> 01:07:49.470
And heuristics actually give
you a very good solution

01:07:49.470 --> 01:07:50.970
because it's much simpler.

01:07:50.970 --> 01:07:54.490
This is real data from the
MBTA, again, from 20 years ago.

01:07:54.490 --> 01:07:57.600
So I'm not saying it's
exactly the same today.

01:07:57.600 --> 01:08:03.760
But I would bet it's not
that different from now

01:08:03.760 --> 01:08:05.270
from what it was then.

