So this is a single MBTA garage.

01:08:09.470 --> 01:08:12.770
This is the Cabot garage, which
is one of the biggest MBTA bus

01:08:12.770 --> 01:08:14.540
garages.

01:08:14.540 --> 01:08:18.890
And for that garage, this
shows the mean number

01:08:18.890 --> 01:08:24.200
of open hours of work on a
daily basis over a timetable.

01:08:24.200 --> 01:08:28.250
So on Mondays, 259 hours
was the mean number

01:08:28.250 --> 01:08:30.620
of hours you had to
cover because you

01:08:30.620 --> 01:08:32.450
didn't have someone available.

01:08:32.450 --> 01:08:34.979
Standard deviation
of that was 36.

01:08:34.979 --> 01:08:38.240
So that's quite variable.

01:08:38.240 --> 01:08:42.109
Tuesday and Wednesday is
lower in terms of absences--

01:08:42.109 --> 01:08:44.210
also quite variable.

01:08:44.210 --> 01:08:47.687
Thursday and particularly
Friday is much higher and also

01:08:47.687 --> 01:08:48.479
even more variable.

01:08:53.310 --> 01:08:57.000
So following our
analysis principles,

01:08:57.000 --> 01:08:59.850
the cumulative density
function, then you

01:08:59.850 --> 01:09:04.630
would expect to want to
allocate your workforce,

01:09:04.630 --> 01:09:10.180
your spare workforce,
reflecting the level of absence.

01:09:10.180 --> 01:09:10.680
But no.

01:09:13.920 --> 01:09:19.160
The MBTA was allocating their
extraboard exactly equally

01:09:19.160 --> 01:09:21.380
across all weekdays--

01:09:21.380 --> 01:09:25.350
20 extraboard operators on
Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday,

01:09:25.350 --> 01:09:26.800
Thursday, Friday, Saturday--

01:09:26.800 --> 01:09:29.270
Wednesday, Thursday,
Friday, lower levels

01:09:29.270 --> 01:09:33.290
on Saturday and Sunday, but the
same percentage, independent

01:09:33.290 --> 01:09:36.319
of the observed level
of difference in absence

01:09:36.319 --> 01:09:40.060
or extra work required
on those days.

01:09:40.060 --> 01:09:45.550
The model showed that if
you optimally reallocated

01:09:45.550 --> 01:09:50.090
the same level of resources,
basically the same level down

01:09:50.090 --> 01:09:52.729
here in terms of
operator days, you

01:09:52.729 --> 01:09:58.430
provide more cover on
Fridays, on Mondays,

01:09:58.430 --> 01:10:03.570
and weekends, and less coverage
on Tuesdays, Wednesdays,

01:10:03.570 --> 01:10:06.720
and Thursdays, reflecting
the absence patterns.

01:10:06.720 --> 01:10:09.521
That's optimizing the daily
level for a particular garage.

01:10:13.580 --> 01:10:17.900
And at that point, they
weren't using part-timers.

01:10:17.900 --> 01:10:22.490
They were using part-timers,
but the part-timers

01:10:22.490 --> 01:10:26.028
were not on the extraboard
and not being used in quite

01:10:26.028 --> 01:10:27.320
the same way that they are now.

01:10:30.110 --> 01:10:33.230
And what you get out of this
is the expected overtime

01:10:33.230 --> 01:10:37.190
hours over the whole
timetable, recognizing

01:10:37.190 --> 01:10:40.940
the variability on
a particular day

01:10:40.940 --> 01:10:43.340
is the expected
level of overtime

01:10:43.340 --> 01:10:53.190
hours over the whole week is
140 hours versus 99 hours.

01:10:53.190 --> 01:10:58.760
So you're saving about 25% to
30% of your overtime costs,

01:10:58.760 --> 01:11:01.910
just by reallocating your
existing workforce more

01:11:01.910 --> 01:11:05.500
effectively across
days of the week.

01:11:05.500 --> 01:11:07.130
This is not rocket science.

01:11:07.130 --> 01:11:09.430
This is actually
pretty easy to do.

01:11:09.430 --> 01:11:11.990
I mean, you can get these
absence figures quite easily

01:11:11.990 --> 01:11:15.800
and implement them.

01:11:15.800 --> 01:11:19.780
So the tactical level findings
are significant variation,

01:11:19.780 --> 01:11:26.140
absence, and required extra work
by garage and by day of week.

01:11:26.140 --> 01:11:31.060
So what would you
expect by garage,

01:11:31.060 --> 01:11:32.920
in terms of absence rates?

01:11:32.920 --> 01:11:35.080
You might expect--
and you'd be right--

01:11:35.080 --> 01:11:37.750
that the most difficult garages
would have the highest absence

01:11:37.750 --> 01:11:38.950
rates.

01:11:38.950 --> 01:11:40.670
Those are tough conditions.

01:11:40.670 --> 01:11:44.110
So if you look at Cabot,
those are very tough routes.

01:11:44.110 --> 01:11:47.380
And so when you do a
system-wide pick that

01:11:47.380 --> 01:11:52.266
allows the operators to select
the garage they work at,

01:11:52.266 --> 01:11:56.610
so the most senior
operators will avoid Cabot.

01:11:56.610 --> 01:11:58.570
So it's the most
junior operators

01:11:58.570 --> 01:12:02.650
that wind up at Cabot on
the most difficult routes.

01:12:02.650 --> 01:12:06.970
Not a great surprise your
absence rate is higher at Cabot

01:12:06.970 --> 01:12:08.710
than it is at Lynn or Quincy--

01:12:08.710 --> 01:12:10.360
nice, comfortable
suburban garages.

01:12:14.340 --> 01:12:15.342
Yeah.

01:12:15.342 --> 01:12:18.037
AUDIENCE: How do you
define a difficult route?

01:12:18.037 --> 01:12:19.250
What constitutes [INAUDIBLE]?

01:12:19.250 --> 01:12:20.250
NIGEL HM WILSON: Oh, OK.

01:12:20.250 --> 01:12:24.750
So there can be any
number of things--

01:12:24.750 --> 01:12:29.390
very heavy traffic, danger of
accidents, danger of assault,

01:12:29.390 --> 01:12:34.650
crime, danger of
altercations among customers,

01:12:34.650 --> 01:12:37.810
passengers on the bus,
altercations with the driver.

01:12:37.810 --> 01:12:42.300
So a number of things like that.

01:12:42.300 --> 01:12:48.480
And so I'm not saying all
the routes in the Lynn garage

01:12:48.480 --> 01:12:49.950
are great routes.

01:12:49.950 --> 01:12:54.420
But compared with operating
in the inner city, which

01:12:54.420 --> 01:12:56.370
is where the Cabot
routes typically serve,

01:12:56.370 --> 01:12:57.468
there is a difference.

01:12:57.468 --> 01:12:59.760
And certainly in Quincy,
there will be a big difference

01:12:59.760 --> 01:13:00.090
as well.

01:13:00.090 --> 01:13:00.590
Yes?

01:13:03.070 --> 01:13:06.510
AUDIENCE: So the workforce
would have differing levels

01:13:06.510 --> 01:13:09.860
of information about which
route or which garage would

01:13:09.860 --> 01:13:11.163
be more difficult [INAUDIBLE]?

01:13:11.163 --> 01:13:12.580
NIGEL HM WILSON:
By word of mouth.

01:13:12.580 --> 01:13:16.320
It's not a sort of a
conscious campaign.

01:13:16.320 --> 01:13:20.580
The idea is basically,
you say, hey,

01:13:20.580 --> 01:13:22.210
we've got a seniority system.

01:13:22.210 --> 01:13:25.860
So you'll get to know other
operators of different depots,

01:13:25.860 --> 01:13:26.910
word of mouth.

01:13:26.910 --> 01:13:29.520
And you'll select, based
on what's available

01:13:29.520 --> 01:13:32.520
when it gets to you of your
place in your seniority list,

01:13:32.520 --> 01:13:34.170
where you want to work.

01:13:34.170 --> 01:13:36.330
And often, it's based
on where you live.

01:13:36.330 --> 01:13:41.185
You don't want to have to
commute from Lynn to Quincy

01:13:41.185 --> 01:13:43.270
every day to do your work.

01:13:43.270 --> 01:13:46.380
So it's a question of
proximity to where you live

01:13:46.380 --> 01:13:52.380
and the ease, the comfort
level you'll have on the routes

01:13:52.380 --> 01:13:55.440
and the conditions that
you'll be operating on.

01:13:55.440 --> 01:13:56.360
OK?

01:13:56.360 --> 01:13:59.300
And the policy of the
MBTA at this point

01:13:59.300 --> 01:14:04.200
was to provide the same level
of cover at every garage.

01:14:04.200 --> 01:14:04.700
Why?

01:14:07.960 --> 01:14:09.850
Their argument that
they articulated to me--

01:14:09.850 --> 01:14:14.095
and obviously, I discussed
this with them extensively--

01:14:14.095 --> 01:14:17.110
they would not dispute the fact
that Cabot has a higher level

01:14:17.110 --> 01:14:19.522
of absence than Quincy or Lynn.

01:14:19.522 --> 01:14:20.230
They accept that.

01:14:20.230 --> 01:14:21.920
That's not in dispute.

01:14:21.920 --> 01:14:23.500
But their argument
would be, you're

01:14:23.500 --> 01:14:29.450
rewarding the manager
of Cabot by giving

01:14:29.450 --> 01:14:32.540
them more manpower if you
recognize the existing absence

01:14:32.540 --> 01:14:33.350
level.

01:14:33.350 --> 01:14:36.700
So they're concerned
about this feedback loop.

01:14:36.700 --> 01:14:40.350
If you have more absence,
you get more manpower.

01:14:40.350 --> 01:14:42.450
To me, that's a
completely backwards way

01:14:42.450 --> 01:14:43.500
of thinking about this.

01:14:43.500 --> 01:14:46.080
You need to have
incentives for the managers

01:14:46.080 --> 01:14:48.570
to do a good job, hopefully.

01:14:48.570 --> 01:14:51.570
But you shouldn't let
that be the motivation

01:14:51.570 --> 01:14:53.370
for making bad
decisions about how

01:14:53.370 --> 01:14:55.440
you use your resources,
which is basically

01:14:55.440 --> 01:14:58.460
what's happening here.

01:14:58.460 --> 01:15:01.520
And they were arguing the same
thing in terms of day of week,

01:15:01.520 --> 01:15:02.120
as well.

01:15:02.120 --> 01:15:05.930
So they were really
fighting that, that concept.

01:15:05.930 --> 01:15:11.540
And I wasn't successful
in persuading them

01:15:11.540 --> 01:15:15.170
that they should really
separate out the management

01:15:15.170 --> 01:15:18.480
incentives from the efficiency
of the decisions they're

01:15:18.480 --> 01:15:18.980
making.

01:15:21.980 --> 01:15:24.660
OK.

01:15:24.660 --> 01:15:25.160
All right.

01:15:25.160 --> 01:15:26.780
The final level--

01:15:26.780 --> 01:15:28.850
I've got a few minutes left--

01:15:28.850 --> 01:15:30.840
is the operational level.

01:15:30.840 --> 01:15:34.520
So again, we've gone from
the one-year planning horizon

01:15:34.520 --> 01:15:39.680
to the timetable planning
horizon for three or four

01:15:39.680 --> 01:15:42.990
months, now down
to the daily level.

01:15:42.990 --> 01:15:44.120
OK.

01:15:44.120 --> 01:15:46.520
So the objective here is
pretty much the same thing.

01:15:46.520 --> 01:15:48.782
We're trying to minimize
the weighted sum of overtime

01:15:48.782 --> 01:15:49.490
and missed trips.

01:15:54.590 --> 01:15:55.263
Oh, I'm sorry.

01:15:55.263 --> 01:15:56.930
I'm still at the
operational level here.

01:16:01.430 --> 01:16:04.830
Yeah, no this is right, sorry.

01:16:04.830 --> 01:16:11.430
So what we want to do here
is decide the report times

01:16:11.430 --> 01:16:17.090
for any unassigned, extra
staff for the next day.

01:16:17.090 --> 01:16:20.110
So as I said, at
12 o'clock today,

01:16:20.110 --> 01:16:22.450
if there were five
operators who had not

01:16:22.450 --> 01:16:28.420
been assigned work for tomorrow
at Cabot, then the MBTA

01:16:28.420 --> 01:16:29.530
manager--

01:16:29.530 --> 01:16:34.460
desk superintendent or whoever
you want to call him or her--

01:16:34.460 --> 01:16:37.600
at Cabot will be
posting the report times

01:16:37.600 --> 01:16:39.640
for those five people tomorrow.

01:16:39.640 --> 01:16:42.070
You don't know what the
absence is going to be.

01:16:42.070 --> 01:16:43.570
You didn't have any
known in advance

01:16:43.570 --> 01:16:46.030
absence to give
them work to cover.

01:16:46.030 --> 01:16:47.950
But you want them
to be available

01:16:47.950 --> 01:16:49.762
so that when you do
get the absences, which

01:16:49.762 --> 01:16:51.970
you don't know about, they
will be in a good position

01:16:51.970 --> 01:16:52.926
to cover them.

01:16:59.140 --> 01:17:02.238
And so this gets into the
most detailed level of this.

01:17:02.238 --> 01:17:03.780
So it's not just a
question of having

01:17:03.780 --> 01:17:08.630
the right number of drivers
available on a particular day.

01:17:08.630 --> 01:17:10.380
It's a question of
having the right number

01:17:10.380 --> 01:17:14.960
of available drivers at
every time of that day.

01:17:14.960 --> 01:17:16.860
That's the problem
we're dealing with here.

01:17:16.860 --> 01:17:19.850
So again, much more
uncertainty about how

01:17:19.850 --> 01:17:27.070
the absence is at 9 o'clock
AM versus 5 o'clock PM.

01:17:27.070 --> 01:17:30.445
And what this is showing
is this glorious concept.

01:17:30.445 --> 01:17:33.220
It used to be called
"slop overtime."

01:17:33.220 --> 01:17:35.320
The MBTA didn't like the
term "slop overtime,"

01:17:35.320 --> 01:17:37.810
so it's now "excess overtime."

01:17:37.810 --> 01:17:40.540
So you have regular
overtime, which is just,

01:17:40.540 --> 01:17:44.690
you didn't have enough
personnel on the payroll.

01:17:44.690 --> 01:17:46.440
And so you had to buy
overtime if you were

01:17:46.440 --> 01:17:48.220
going to deliver the service.

01:17:48.220 --> 01:17:52.850
Excess overtime is where, in
theory you have enough people

01:17:52.850 --> 01:17:55.220
to cover the needs, but
they're not available

01:17:55.220 --> 01:17:59.070
when you want them to be,
because you couldn't make

01:17:59.070 --> 01:18:02.370
perfect decisions about when
they should show up to make

01:18:02.370 --> 01:18:05.000
sure they're productive.

01:18:05.000 --> 01:18:08.240
So here, I'm showing,
here, this is

01:18:08.240 --> 01:18:12.890
time of day from 5:00 AM to
1:00 AM the next morning.

01:18:15.430 --> 01:18:21.790
This shows the open run
profile, OK, like that.

01:18:24.610 --> 01:18:29.320
Sorry, this is the open
run profile like this.

01:18:29.320 --> 01:18:32.260
And this is the available cover
profile, based on your report

01:18:32.260 --> 01:18:36.160
time decisions, like this.

01:18:36.160 --> 01:18:38.710
And so what this shows is
that you have these periods

01:18:38.710 --> 01:18:43.900
here and here and
here, where you

01:18:43.900 --> 01:18:50.290
had more operators available
than you had work to cover.

01:18:50.290 --> 01:18:53.940
And so that means that there
were other periods of the day

01:18:53.940 --> 01:18:56.790
here and here and
here, where you

01:18:56.790 --> 01:18:58.140
didn't have enough operators.

01:18:58.140 --> 01:19:00.270
You had the right
number on the whole day,

01:19:00.270 --> 01:19:04.020
you just didn't have them at
the right time in the day.

01:19:04.020 --> 01:19:06.240
And it's not just you
made bad decisions,

01:19:06.240 --> 01:19:09.090
it's that this is stochastic.

01:19:09.090 --> 01:19:10.568
You can't make
perfect decisions.

01:19:10.568 --> 01:19:12.110
So you've got to
expect there's going

01:19:12.110 --> 01:19:19.410
to be some excess
overtime built in here.

01:19:19.410 --> 01:19:22.470
And this is the
excess overtime curve.

01:19:22.470 --> 01:19:26.427
And I will wrap this up in
four minutes, I promise.

01:19:26.427 --> 01:19:27.760
I may not go through everything.

01:19:27.760 --> 01:19:31.630
But I'll cover most
of what we want.

01:19:31.630 --> 01:19:34.650
So this, on the x-axis,
is the available cover

01:19:34.650 --> 01:19:36.540
minus the required cover.

01:19:36.540 --> 01:19:41.070
So again, if it's
a perfect balance,

01:19:41.070 --> 01:19:42.990
excess cover minus
required cover

01:19:42.990 --> 01:19:47.340
is 0 because you
had a perfect fit.

01:19:47.340 --> 01:19:49.620
But what that gives you
is the greatest number

01:19:49.620 --> 01:19:51.120
of excess overtime hours.

01:19:51.120 --> 01:19:54.710
Because unless you made
every decision perfectly,

01:19:54.710 --> 01:19:57.200
you're going to have
excess overtime hours.

01:19:57.200 --> 01:20:00.980
If you go way out here,
you had far more people

01:20:00.980 --> 01:20:02.930
available than you needed.

01:20:02.930 --> 01:20:04.680
So you shouldn't have
any access overtime,

01:20:04.680 --> 01:20:07.040
even if you make
lousy decisions.

01:20:07.040 --> 01:20:10.380
You put them out any
time, they'll be covered.

01:20:10.380 --> 01:20:12.300
And you put them
out-- if you have

01:20:12.300 --> 01:20:15.030
far fewer people available
than you require,

01:20:15.030 --> 01:20:16.050
you'll be out here.

01:20:16.050 --> 01:20:18.900
And you shouldn't have any
access overtime either,

01:20:18.900 --> 01:20:22.310
because you don't
have to be very

01:20:22.310 --> 01:20:25.310
good to make decisions which
will have these people be fully

01:20:25.310 --> 01:20:27.305
employed.

01:20:27.305 --> 01:20:30.100
OK.

01:20:30.100 --> 01:20:33.970
So it's when you have
this exact balance,

01:20:33.970 --> 01:20:36.220
you have to make every
decision perfectly

01:20:36.220 --> 01:20:37.617
to avoid excess overtime.

01:20:37.617 --> 01:20:39.034
And you're never
going to do that.

01:20:44.010 --> 01:20:47.530
OK, so I've got
some results here,

01:20:47.530 --> 01:20:51.670
which you can go
through on your own.

01:20:51.670 --> 01:20:56.410
And I don't think I need
to cover this specifically.

01:20:56.410 --> 01:20:59.760
But let me get to the
conclusion on this.

01:21:02.520 --> 01:21:04.980
The analysis we did on
this level of the model

01:21:04.980 --> 01:21:10.860
shows, because of the natural
peaking in work requirements,

01:21:10.860 --> 01:21:13.380
that you have much more
service in the peak

01:21:13.380 --> 01:21:16.320
than in the middle
of the day, the base,

01:21:16.320 --> 01:21:19.770
it doesn't matter that
absence rates are actually

01:21:19.770 --> 01:21:22.380
higher in the peak than they
are in the middle of the day.

01:21:22.380 --> 01:21:24.570
Because your
decisions are driven

01:21:24.570 --> 01:21:28.370
by the same underlying dynamic.

01:21:28.370 --> 01:21:33.770
And so you just can make
good report time decisions,

01:21:33.770 --> 01:21:42.090
based on the average absence
rate on that day at that depot.

01:21:42.090 --> 01:21:44.760
So you don't have to go into
super detailed analysis, which

01:21:44.760 --> 01:21:47.510
is good news.

01:21:47.510 --> 01:21:51.050
And in fact, you can
wind up with having

01:21:51.050 --> 01:21:56.420
a ranked list of report times
that the desk manager at Cabot

01:21:56.420 --> 01:21:59.550
can just work off that
list for tomorrow,

01:21:59.550 --> 01:22:01.580
based on the number
of unassigned cover

01:22:01.580 --> 01:22:03.050
operators you have.

01:22:03.050 --> 01:22:05.540
And it will always give you
a good solution, as opposed

01:22:05.540 --> 01:22:10.860
to the desk manager making
decisions de novo, every day.

01:22:10.860 --> 01:22:17.450
This is a very simple decision
support tool that can help.

01:22:17.450 --> 01:22:19.010
So the operational
level findings--

01:22:19.010 --> 01:22:22.010
significant improvements
are possible,

01:22:22.010 --> 01:22:25.070
can reduce the overtime
and missed trips,

01:22:25.070 --> 01:22:27.920
and a single set of report times
can be used across all weekdays

01:22:27.920 --> 01:22:31.160
and seasons for each garage.

01:22:31.160 --> 01:22:34.430
Separate ranked report times
for Saturdays and Sundays,

01:22:34.430 --> 01:22:36.290
and constant absence
rates can be assumed

01:22:36.290 --> 01:22:37.870
by hour of day and day of week.

01:22:37.870 --> 01:22:40.330
Those are the main conclusions.

01:22:40.330 --> 01:22:43.280
OK, sorry I raced
towards the end.

01:22:43.280 --> 01:22:45.380
But I'm available.

01:22:45.380 --> 01:22:48.888
I am retiring, as
Gabriel well knows,

01:22:48.888 --> 01:22:49.930
at the end of the summer.

01:22:49.930 --> 01:22:54.110
This is probably my last lecture
as a non-retired MIT faculty

01:22:54.110 --> 01:22:54.980
member.

01:22:54.980 --> 01:22:58.310
It's been fun doing it with you.

01:22:58.310 --> 01:23:00.120
And I'm around.

01:23:00.120 --> 01:23:02.960
And I will be around after
the end of the summer as well.

01:23:02.960 --> 01:23:05.420
Just I won't be
being paid by MIT.

01:23:05.420 --> 01:23:07.340
So if anyone wants to
discuss any of this

01:23:07.340 --> 01:23:09.810
or go through any of
the background topics,

01:23:09.810 --> 01:23:12.080
please feel free to come see me.

01:23:12.080 --> 01:23:12.830
OK?

